WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:09.141 --> 00:00:12.379
Someday, I will die.

00:00:13.546 --> 00:00:15.214
But should I?

00:00:15.247 --> 00:00:16.616
If I was offered
a longer life,

00:00:16.649 --> 00:00:18.785
I would take that
in a second.

00:00:18.818 --> 00:00:21.687
But how long is too long?

00:00:21.720 --> 00:00:26.092
Is death something
I should deny forever,

00:00:26.125 --> 00:00:30.263
or is death and the role
it plays in the universe

00:00:30.296 --> 00:00:33.199
something I am better off
accepting?

00:00:56.322 --> 00:00:58.257
I want to start by looking
at a particular way

00:00:58.290 --> 00:01:01.428
death affects how we live
and treat one another.

00:01:03.496 --> 00:01:05.398 line:0%
Terror Management Theory

00:01:05.431 --> 00:01:07.700 line:0%
proposes that people
like you and me

00:01:07.733 --> 00:01:11.504 line:0%
manage the terror
of death's inevitability

00:01:11.537 --> 00:01:13.773
by embracing cultural values.

00:01:13.806 --> 00:01:17.777
That the more aware a person is
of their own mortality,

00:01:17.810 --> 00:01:19.445
the more vehemently
they will enforce

00:01:19.478 --> 00:01:22.615
their particular views
of the world onto others.

00:01:22.648 --> 00:01:25.418
<i>Created by social psychologists
 Sheldon Solomon,</i>

00:01:25.451 --> 00:01:27.720
<i> Jeff Greenberg
 and Tom Pyszczynski,</i>

00:01:27.753 --> 00:01:30.723
<i> Terror Management Theory,
 or TMT,</i>

00:01:30.756 --> 00:01:34.360
<i> suggests that, often,
 we are afraid of change</i>

00:01:34.393 --> 00:01:36.696
<i> because we're afraid
 of death.</i>

00:01:36.729 --> 00:01:38.331
<i> Each one of us
 has a worldview,</i>

00:01:38.364 --> 00:01:39.866
<i> a set of beliefs,
 customs and norms</i>

00:01:39.899 --> 00:01:42.635
<i> we identify with
 that can live on</i>

00:01:42.668 --> 00:01:44.770
<i>after our physical bodies die.</i>

00:01:44.803 --> 00:01:48.207
<i> TMT suggest that rises
 in nationalism and prejudice</i>

00:01:48.240 --> 00:01:52.545
<i> are correlated with rises
 in the salience of mortality.</i>

00:01:52.578 --> 00:01:54.614
<i> That is, how present
 the inevitability of death is</i>

00:01:54.647 --> 00:01:56.215
<i> in people's minds.</i>

00:01:56.248 --> 00:01:58.751
<i>Now this role that death plays
 fascinates me,</i>

00:01:58.784 --> 00:02:01.687 line:0%
<i> and two of TMT's originators,
 Jeff and Sheldon,</i>

00:02:01.720 --> 00:02:03.422 line:0%
<i> have agreed to work with me
 on a pilot study</i>

00:02:03.455 --> 00:02:05.558
<i> of Terror Management Theory</i>

00:02:05.591 --> 00:02:08.595
<i> and real-life reminders
 of death.</i>

00:02:10.296 --> 00:02:12.932
What's your hypothesis today?

00:02:12.965 --> 00:02:16.802
Well, I think we're going
to hope for the participants

00:02:16.835 --> 00:02:19.172
who are reminded
of their mortality

00:02:19.205 --> 00:02:22.842
to be more punitive
in their assessments.

